\contentsline {table}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Evaluation platform. All prove-mode measurements are local single-machine runs with no network or dev-mode acceleration unless stated.}}{62}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces PLUM single-signature verification, prove mode, $\lambda =80$, M5~Pro 24~GB. We refer to the three SP1 arms as \emph {Cell~1} (no precompile), \emph {Cell~2} (Griffin-$\mathbb {F}_p^{192}$ precompile), and \emph {Cell~3} (software SHA-3 control) throughout. The precompile-free baseline does not complete; the precompile arm completes in $14.25$~min. The SHA-3 arm is a \emph {control} (PLUM with a standard hash computed in software, no hash precompile, only the shared \texttt {UINT256\_MUL} field-arithmetic precompile active), not a deployable PLUM variant. The Cell~2 and Cell~3 prove times are means of three fixed-config runs on a clean machine (2026-06-30, \S \ref {ssec:headline}); a 2026-06-13 same-session pair gave Cell~2 $17.81$~min and Cell~3 $16.15$~min ($n=2$), and a single 2026-05 run measured Cell~2 $32.53$~min, the high figure attributed to machine-state contamination and not reproduced under replication. $^\dag $Cell~2 prove time is the mean of three runs, $14.25$~min (range $14.05$--$14.61$, ${\approx }14.2$~GB peak RSS). $^\ddag $RISC~Zero receipt-verify wall-clock not separately logged; the receipt verified.}}{63}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Aurora over a single Loquat-verification R1CS, M5~Pro 24~GB; mean of three solo runs with the per-run range in parentheses (run records in \texttt {docs/measurements/pub\_hardening\_20260610}). This is the \emph {Loquat}-instantiated circuit over $\mathbb {F}_{p^2}$ ($127$-bit base)~\cite {10.1007/978-981-96-0957-4_3} at single-verification scope; the full BDEC relation is two such verifications ($\approx $twice this), not run statically. Prover time includes Aurora parameter setup but is not a recompile-time measurement (\S \ref {ssec:churn-eval}). Achieved security $107.5$ bits, below the $128$ target. Verification \texttt {ACCEPT} in every run.}}{65}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Same-scheme substrate comparison: one Loquat verification, $\lambda =80$, M5~Pro 24~GB, three solo runs per leg, neither zero-knowledge. The Aurora leg is the mean of Table~\ref {tab:aurora-ref}; the SP1 leg is the range of three runs ($44.4$, $47.4$, $64.0$~min) under the documented reduced-memory configuration (\S \ref {ssec:settings-justify}), succinct core STARK, peak RSS $14.1$--$15.4$~GiB, execute-mode cost $397{,}227{,}544$ cycles (run records in \texttt {docs/measurements/pub\_hardening\_20260610}). Only the substrate differs (native R1CS versus zkVM emulation); the $12$--$17\times $ prover-time gap is the cost of the zkVM substrate for this scheme. This isolates the substrate for \emph {Loquat}; it does not transfer to PLUM, which has no $127$-bit Aurora harness.}}{66}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Cycle-level cost attribution, PLUM verification, SHA-3 hasher, $\lambda =128$, \emph {execute mode}. Routing field arithmetic through the host precompile (and removing redundant reductions) cuts $37.9\%$ of SP1 cycles and $70.5\%$ of RISC~Zero cycles; RISC~Zero's larger reduction reflects its heavier per-multiplication baseline emulation ($6{,}625$ cycles/mul at baseline, falling to $1{,}826$ with the precompile path, against SP1's baseline of about $2{,}567$ cycles/mul).}}{67}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces BDEC credential relations, $\lambda =80$, M5~Pro 24~GB. On RISC~Zero, execute mode validates the honest-input path of CreGen ($9.4\times 10^{9}$ cycles, ${\approx }4.69\times 10^{9}$ per signature verification); its succinct prove yielded no receipt, from an internal-verifier rejection rather than a resource limit (\S \ref {ssec:cregen-anomaly}), not used as a feasibility result. On SP1 both relations complete a \emph {succinct} prove: CreGen in $26.98$ and $31.11$~min, ShowCre in $40.15$ and $44.24$~min at $k{=}1$ and $58.14$~min at $k{=}2$. These receipts are succinct STARKs and are \emph {not} zero-knowledge; the $k{=}2$ figure agrees with the additive cost model within ${\approx }3.3\%$ of the $(k{+}2)/3$ projection from the $k{=}1$ mean (run records \texttt {docs/measurements/pub\_hardening\_20260611} and \texttt {audit5\_campaign\_20260612}).}}{68}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Proof-mode feasibility matrix. Of the modes \emph {produced} on the target hardware by the zkVMs, none is dependably zero-knowledge: the SP1 rows are not zero-knowledge, the RISC~Zero receipt carries no formally established zero-knowledge guarantee, and the only zero-knowledge mode the zkVM toolchain exposes (row~3, a pairing wrap) is neither post-quantum nor produced as the toolchain ships, which is the dual obstruction. The zero-knowledge mode that is produced on this hardware is the static-circuit Aurora run (last row; \S \ref {ssec:aurora-ref}). \textsuperscript {$\dagger $}The zero-knowledge-enabled Aurora run is now measured (last row); the zk-disabled row is retained for comparison. Both Aurora rows achieve $107.5$ bits, below the $\lambda =128$ target. \textsuperscript {$\ddagger $}RISC~Zero's succinct receipt carries zero-knowledge blinding, but the vendor disclaims a formal zero-knowledge guarantee, so we treat the receipt as not dependably zero-knowledge~\cite {risc0zkadvisory,l2beatzk} (Section~\ref {sec:security}). The SHA-3 row is a control, not a deployable PLUM variant.}}{102}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Circuit/parameter regeneration footprint ($N_{\mathsf {circ}},N_{\mathsf {param}}$ of Definition~\ref {def:update-churn}). The static-circuit regime regenerates and re-audits its R1CS and constraint-dependent parameters on every localised change; the zkVM absorbs a change as a guest-program edit, leaving the universal relation unchanged ($N_{\mathsf {circ}}=N_{\mathsf {param}}=0$), except where the change crosses the precompile boundary. \textsuperscript {$\ast $}The Loquat~$\to $~PLUM swap moves the hash field from $\mathbb {F}_{p^2}$ (127-bit) to the 199-bit $\mathbb {F}_p$, so the field-specific Griffin AIR is regenerated (\S \ref {ssec:update-churn} carve-out). The components $N_{\mathsf {src}},N_{\mathsf {audit}}$ are reported in prose below.}}{103}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Per-change recompile components for a non-preprocessing (Aurora) versus a preprocessing (Fractal) transparent argument on the same $127$-bit-field harness, M5~Pro 24~GB. The $2^{10}$--$2^{14}$ rows are synthetic R1CS instances; the $2^{19}$ row is the single-Loquat-verification relation at the BDEC building-block size. Aurora has no per-circuit indexer (parameter setup flat at ${\sim }\mu $s, so $R_{\mathsf {static}}$ stays sub-second); Fractal's indexer is superlinear and exceeds $24$~GB at the $2^{19}$ size (OOM mid-indexer). The zkVM regenerates no circuit.}}{103}{}%
